Package org.sakaiproject.genericdao.api.annotations

These interceptors provide safe ways to get to the data being handled by the generic dao methods before and after they are called

See:
          Description

Annotation Types Summary
PersistentColumnIndexed Indicates that a persistent column should be indexed, can optionally specify a name for the index (should be less than 30 chars)
Should be placed on a field/method in a persistent class
PersistentColumnMappingPolicy Defines a persistent column mapping policy for this class, this will default to using the MappingPolicy.FIELD_NAMES policy by default or if this annotation is not set on the persistent class
Should be placed on the persistent class
PersistentColumnName Indicates the name of the column which this field maps to, if this is not specified then the default PersistentColumnMappingPolicy for this class will be used
Should be placed on a field/method in a persistent class
Similar to the JPA Column annotation (this is a subset of that functionality)
PersistentForeignKey Indicates that this column represents a foreign key value which points to another persistent object, if this is a foreign key in the database to a non-persistent table then use PersistentTransient to indicate it should be ignored
You can optionally specify a foreign table name and foreign id column manually if desired
Should be placed on a field/method in a persistent class
PersistentId Marks a getter method or field as the unique id for a persistent object, the convention is to run toString on the return from the "getId" method or the value in the "id" field
Should be placed on a field/method in a persistent class
NOTE: This annotation should only be used once in a class, the getter method must take no arguments and return an object
Can also use the JPA Id annotation with the same effect
PersistentTableName Allows the persistent table name to be set to something specific rather than defaulting to the autogenerated one based on the class name, the value provided is the table name and should be less than 30 characters long
Example: MY_TABLE_NAME
Should be placed on the persistent class
Similar to the JPA Table annotation.
PersistentTransient Marks a field on a persistent class as being transient (i.e. indicates that it should not be persisted or retrieved from the database) Should be placed on a field/method in a persistent class
Can also use the JPA Transient annotation with the same effect
